SIMPLE: prick
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prick
<hw>Prick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>prica</ets>,
<ets>pricca</ets>, <ets>pricu</ets>; akin to LG. <ets>prick</ets>,
<ets>pricke</ets>, D. <ets>prik</ets>, Dan. <ets>prik</ets>,
<ets>prikke</ets>, Sw. <ets>prick</ets>. Cf. <er>Prick</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which pricks, penetrates, or
punctures; a sharp and slender thing; a pointed instrument; a goad; a
spur, etc.; a point; a skewer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pins, wooden <qex>pricks</qex>, nails, sprigs of rosemary.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is hard for thee to kick against the <qex>pricks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts ix. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of pricking, or the sensation of being
pricked; a sharp, stinging pain; figuratively, remorse.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>pricks</xex> of conscience.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>A. Tucker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mark made by a pointed instrument; a puncture; a
point.</def> Hence: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A point or mark on the dial,
noting the hour.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>prick</xex>
of noon.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The point on a target
at which an archer aims; the mark; the pin.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧They that
shooten nearest the <xex>prick</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>A mark denoting degree; degree; pitch.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>prick</xex> of highest praise forth
to advance.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>A mathematical
point; -- regularly used in old English translations of Euclid.</def>
<sd>(e)</sd> <def>The footprint of a hare.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A small roll; <as>as, a
<ex>prick</ex> of spun yarn; a <ex>prick</ex> of tobacco.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prick
<hw>Prick</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pricked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pricking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>prician</ets>; akin to
LG. <ets>pricken</ets>, D. <ets>prikken</ets>, Dan. <ets>prikke</ets>,
Sw. <ets>pricka</ets>. See <er>Prick</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Prink</er>, <er>Prig</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pierce
slightly with a sharp-pointed instrument or substance; to make a
puncture in, or to make by puncturing; to drive a fine point into;
<as>as, to <ex>prick</ex> one with a pin, needle, etc.; to
<ex>prick</ex> a card; to <ex>prick</ex> holes in paper.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fix by the point; to attach or hang by
puncturing; <as>as, to <ex>prick</ex> a knife into a board</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Sir I. Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cooks <qex>prick</qex> it [a slice] on a prong of iron.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To mark or denote by a puncture; to designate by
pricking; to choose; to mark; -- sometimes with
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some who are <qex>pricked</qex> for sheriffs.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let the soldiers for duty be carefully <qex>pricked</qex> off.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those many, then, shall die: their names are
<qex>pricked</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mark the outline of by puncturing; to trace or
form by pricking; to mark by punctured dots; <as>as, to <ex>prick</ex> a
pattern for embroidery; to <ex>prick</ex> the notes of a musical
composition.</as></def> <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To ride or guide with spurs; to spur; to goad; to
incite; to urge on; -- sometimes with <xex>on</xex>, or
<xex>off</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>pricketh</qex> his blind horse over the fallows.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The season <qex>pricketh</qex> every gentle heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My duty <qex>pricks</qex> me on to utter that.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To affect with sharp pain; to sting, as with
remorse.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I was <xex>pricked</xex> with some reproof.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now when they heard this, they were <qex>pricked</qex> in their
heart.</q> <rj><qau>Acts ii. 37.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To make sharp; to erect into a point; to raise, as
something pointed; -- said especially of the ears of an animal, as a
horse or dog; and usually followed by <xex>up</xex>; -- hence, <xex>to
prick up the ears</xex>, to listen sharply; to have the attention and
interest strongly engaged.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The courser . . .
<xex>pricks</xex> up his ears.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To render acid or pungent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To dress; to prink; -- usually with
<xex>up</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Naut)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To run a middle seam
through, as the cloth of a sail.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To trace on a
chart, as a ship's course.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To drive a nail into
(a horse's foot), so as to cause lameness.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To
nick.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prick</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Prick
<hw>Prick</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be punctured; to
suffer or feel a sharp pain, as by puncture; <as>as, a sore finger
<ex>pricks</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spur onward; to ride on horseback.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A gentle knight was <qex>pricking</qex> on the plain.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become sharp or acid; to turn sour, as
wine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To aim at a point or mark.</def>
<rj><au>Hawkins.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prick-eared</ent>⟦br⟧
